            "chars": "<p id=\"docs-internal-guid-b85bff17-7fff-f5e6-2241-e581fd624252\" dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">HT.I.L1&nbsp;</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><strong>Mem: Write and calculate the story in the old monthly Nos.</strong></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">This leading memoranda makes a fascinating accompaniment to the half-sheet on which Dickens &ldquo;calculates&rdquo; how much of his writing would be required to fill &ldquo;about five pages of Household Words&rdquo; each week (see HT.Mems.L2). <em>Hard Times</em> is the only novel that Dickens published in weekly installments for which he kept a complete set of Working Notes. Dickens&rsquo;s decision to use the Working Note system goes hand-in-hand with this memorandum to &ldquo;write and calculate the story in the old monthly N[umbers],&rdquo; since it is unclear how this system&ndash;which he had developed over his previous three novels (<em>Dombey and Son</em>, <em>David Copperfield</em>, and<em> Bleak House</em>)&ndash;could be adapted or translated to weekly composition. Dickens&rsquo;s description of the monthly number as &ldquo;old&rdquo; has a sentimental feel, given that the final installment of <em>Bleak House</em> appeared in September 1853, less than six months prior to his beginning work on Hard Times. This compositional format, then, is &ldquo;old&rdquo; more in the sense of well-established and familiar at this point in Dickens&rsquo;s career. See the Critical Introduction for more on the challenges of the weekly serial. </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"
